Tutorial 1 - Introduction to ThreeJS

13 steps

Did you know that we can create, view and interact with our very own 3D environment on our web browser? With ThreeJS, we are now able to do that.

ThreeJS is one of several JavaScript libraries that enables you to build a 3D environment seamlessly. ThreeJS is built on the core technology of HTML, CSS and JavaScript. When the web was first created, it was meant to only support images, followed by videos. Now as technology is ubiquitous, handheld and personal computing devices have advanced to handle more complicated workloads, like rendering a 3D environment, right at the palm of your hand.

We will read an article about ThreeJS and we will get started by building our very first web application with ThreeJS on VanillaJS (plain JavaScript without additional libraries or frameworks). We will use Vite to initialise our project and create a local server for us to test our website in real time. Let’s get started!

For technical help, be sure to join our StackUp Discord and head to the 🆘｜general-help channel.
Join us on Discord

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to

  • Grasp the foundational knowledge of Classes
  • Differentiate between using classes and functions
  • Create private functions and variables within classes
  • Recognise the variable scope of how variables can be used throughout the JavaScript file
  • Create an instance of a class and to create a super-class

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 13

  • Step 1: Overview of Installation

    We will be writing our HTML, CSS and JavaScript using a Front-End tool called Vite. Some of you might have recalled that when we developed our web applications with React and React Native, we would run a local environment server on our terminal. Well in VanillaJS, we can expect the same experience with Vite. It enables us to not only view our code changes live in our web browser, but it also comes with out of the box features that makes developers’ life much simpler.

    You may head down to this article to read more about Vite.

    Without further ado, let’s start the installation process to set up our environment for ThreeJS. Since this is a JavaScript based project, we will need to install Node Package Manager (NPM). Once we have done so, we will install the Vite Command Line Interface into our platform as well.

    Since we will be creating a basic web application with ThreeJS, you should read this article to learn more about the ThreeJS.

  • Step 2: Installation of Node JS

    Let us install the tools we need for Vite. We will need to install a JavaScript Package manager called Node. This will allow us to install JavaScript dependencies we need into our machine. Go to this link to install Node into your machine.

    Then, select the installer for the machine’s operating system. It will install an executable installer for seamless installation.

    Go to your machine’s file directory to look for the executable file and run it. It should install Node.js and npm.

    Once you have opened the installer, follow the on-screen steps to safely install the file into your machine. Node will then install some packages for you to install dependencies for any JavaScript project you may have.

  • Step 3: Project Workspace Setup

    Now, create a folder in your computer. Rename this folder to StackUp-ThreeJS. This will be the root folder for the projects we will embarking on for this module three tutorials. Using a code editor of your choice, open the folder that we just created.

    Open the terminal, the current working directory should be the root folder you have created (i.e. StackUp-ThreeJS). If the current working directory does not reflect the root folder, you can use the cd command followed by the path to your folder.

  • Step 4: Installation of Vite

    Now, we will need to install Vite’s Command Line Interface (CLI) into our computer. Using Vite’s CLI, we will have access to other tools that front-end developers use. Simply enter the following command into your terminal. 

    npm install vite --save -g

    We use npm to install all the dependencies we need for this project. In this context, npm means Node Package Manager and for most command line tools, the first word is usually the program or app responsible for that command. The next word install is the command for that program. For this case, install means it will download the relevant packages into our machine and install it into our machine.

    Next is -g which is known as a flag. Flags are usually optional and not needed. However, there are additional commands to be added to the current command function. In this case, “-g” for node means “Global”. Any packages installed in this will be stored in a Global directory in your local machine. This means that any project that requires this package can refer to this package without having to install it in the future.

  • Step 5: Project Initialisation

    Finally, we will use the terminal to interface and initialise a Vite Project with JavaScript. Simply enter the following commands to your terminal. Do ensure that your current working directory is the root directory you have created in Step 3. 

    npm create vite

    Initialise with Vite

    The command above is to initialise the project with Vite. You might be prompted to install a create-vite package, indicate y. Once you have done that, you will be prompted to enter the name of the project. Enter introduction-three-js in your terminal.

    Selection of Framework

    Once that is done, you will be asked to select the framework of the project you would like to use. In this case, select Vanilla by hitting the Enter key. You can move around the options by using the “UP ARROW” and “DOWN ARROW” keys on your keyboard. The item that is currently selected will be underlined.

    Choice of Programming Language

    Once you have selected “Vanilla”, select JavaScript as our programming language. The item that is currently selected will be underlined.

    Once you have done the proper initialisation, you will need to run three commands. Now, run the following commands one by one in your terminal as shown below. 

    cd introduction-three-js
npm install three
npm run dev

    In the code as shown above, the first line will change the current working directory to the project directory we initialised with Vite. Next, the second line will install the dependencies we need, in this project, we will need to have threejs installed. You might be wondering why it is install three instead of “install threejs”. This is because the package on NPM is called “three”. As a bonus tip, when we run “npm install <name of package>”, npm will also index the dependencies listed on “package.json” to determine if any of the packages listed in that file is missing from the project folder. If any of the packages are missing, npm will install the packages onto our project.

    Lastly, the last command is to set up and run our local development server as we develop our web application. This local development server has a great benefit which grants us hot-reloading, which is the ability to see our code changes live.

    Good to Know

    As you host any JavaScript projects on Git services like GitHub, one of your folders in your project, “node_modules” will not be stored on your repository as it is ignored by default in your “.gitignore” file. Instead, the names, versions and other information will be stored in the “package.json” file.

    Each time when cloning the repository to your local machine, you will need to run “npm install”, which will reinstall all the dependencies your project need as listed in “package.json”.

  • Step 6: Index.html

    Now we are finally done with the project installation and setup. Before diving into the code, let us first explore the project directory that is generated by Vite. Firstly, if you have followed our Web Development with React campaign, you may have realised that there is a “public” folder where we can store any media, files and assets that can be accessed by our users. There is a main.js file for our JavaScript code. There is also an index.html file which will be the base file that our web application will be built on. Like all other JavaScript based projects, there is a package.json file and a “node_modules” folder.

    Open your index.html file and replace the existing code with the code shown below. 

    <!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Introduction to Three.JS</title>
    <style>
      body { margin: 0; }
      canvas { display: block; }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div id="app"></div>
    <script type="module" src="/main.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
    HTML

    In this web application, we will be writing internal CSS styling as seen in lines 7 and 8. Next, we have an empty <div> element in line 12. That <div> element has an id, “app”. Later, in main.js we will be adding a renderer into this div. As such, we will need to have an empty <div> element. Lastly, in the next line, line 13, we will add a module script main.js and that is how we can add scripts to our project.

  • Step 7: Setting the 3D Scene

    Now, we will be touching on the logic part of the web application. Open main.js and replace the code with the one shown below.

    import * as THREE from 'three';

// Create the scene
const scene = new THREE.Scene();

// Create the camera
const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
camera.position.z = 5;

// Create the renderer
const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ antialias: true });
renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
document.getElementById('app').appendChild(renderer.domElement);
    JavaScript

    In ThreeJS, we refer to 3D objects as meshes. A Mesh constitutes a geometry and a material. Before we start adding any meshes to our project, we will first need to define the properties of the scene. In line 4, we create an instance of a class. For this project, it is how we create a new instance of the THREE.Scene() class. Next in line 7, we will create a perspective camera which will be assigned to the main renderer. In line 13, we will also assign the renderer to the empty <div> element we have created in the previous step.

  • Step 8: Adding Meshes to the Environment

    In this step, we will learn how we can programmatically add meshes into our environment. Before we add it, we need to be familiar with some basic principles of 3D positioning and orientation. They are, positioning an object, scaling an object and rotating an object. In these 3 basic principles, each of them comes with the X, Y, and Z axis. Refer to the image as shown below.

    In this image, you will see that Y is responsible for the height. Traditionally, in a 2D space, it is just the X and the Y axis. Now, as we deal with a 3D environment, we can scale, move and rotate our meshes along the X, Y and Z axis.

    Now open up your main.js file and add the code below.

    // Create a geometry (a cube in this case)
const geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry();
const material = new THREE.MeshPhongMaterial({ color: 0x00ff00 });
const cube = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, material);
scene.add(cube);

// Create a point light
const pointLight = new THREE.PointLight(0xffffff);
pointLight.position.set(5, 5, 5);
scene.add(pointLight);

// Create an ambient light
const ambientLight = new THREE.AmbientLight(0x404040);
scene.add(ambientLight);
    JavaScript

    In this code above, before we create a mesh, we will need to specify which shape and material we would like to add. Once we do that, we will parse the material and geometry object into the THREE.mesh() class to create an instance of a mesh (lines 15 to 19).

    In line 21, we will add a Point Light to the environment. Since this is a virtual space, we will need to add virtual artificial lighting to the environment. Without this lighting, our users will not get to see the elements in the environment. In line 22, there is a number: “0xfffff”, this is also known as a hexadecimal number. It is to specify the colour code of which colour to add for the lighting. A hexadecimal in JavaScript can be denoted as a “0x” in front of a string of numbers of letters. A hexadecimal number can also be written as: “#FFFFFF” as well. Hexadecimals are base 16 numbers that are represented with digits from 0 to 9 and letters from A to F. We will also add ambient light to fill the area as well.

    Did you know that in photography, photographers use 3 point lighting, which uses the same type of lights and techniques we have in ThreeJS to do their photography. They use a key light which is also like our Point Light, Fill Light, and Back light. You may also try to apply the same techniques they use in your 3D environment as well to make it look more realistic. Find out more here.

    By now, your main.js code should be similar to the image below.

  • Step 9: Animating our Meshes

    As part of the interactivity and the looks of the website, an animation of the meshes will make a huge difference on how immersive the website is. To animate our meshes, we will need to create a function and change the position, scale or rotation in that same function we have created. Using the same file, main.js add the following code to the end of the file.

    // Animation function
function animate() {
  requestAnimationFrame(animate);

  // Rotate the cube
  cube.rotation.x += 0.01;
  cube.rotation.y += 0.01;

  // Render the scene with the camera
  renderer.render(scene, camera);
}

// Start the animation
animate();
    JavaScript

    This code sets up a continuous animation loop using requestAnimationFrame() (line 32). The animate() function (line 43) is called repeatedly, updating the cube's rotation angles to create a rotating effect. The renderer.render() call (line 39) renders the updated scene on the screen, resulting in a smooth animation of a 3D cube continuously rotating around both the x and y axes.

    Since lines 35 and 36 are responsible for moving the cube in a rotating motion, we can adjust the speed of the cube by changing the magnitude of each turn.

    By now, your main.js should have 43 lines of code.

  • Step 10: Building Our Application

    And that is it! Congratulations on making it to this point. Once we are satisfied with our project, it is time to build it for the web. What Vite will do is compile the code base across multiple files into one HTML file. Open a new terminal and have the present working directory as introduction-three-js. Once you have done so, run the following command.

    npm run build

    This code will simply create a build of the application and place the build into a new folder called dist. Everything within this folder is the final product that can be now used in production. 

  • Step 11: Project Initialisation and Code Deployment (With Firebase)

    You can host your static site on Firebase, Vercel or Netlify. This tutorial provides instructions for Firebase (this step) and Netlify (next step). You can choose one of the three web hosts.

    Before we can upload our web application to Firebase, we will need to tell Firebase that this project is a Firebase project. If you have yet to install Firebase CLI tools, you are strongly advised to go through the Installation to Firebase tutorial.

    Now, within your code editor, open up the terminal and enter the following command.

    firebase login

    This will redirect us to our web browser. We will need to log in to our Google Account on the web browser as Firebase is a Google service. Behind the scenes, Google is trying to authenticate your account to grant access to your terminal. Upon successful login, you may return to your code editor. You should be able to see a success message on the terminal.

    Next, we will need to initialise this project to our Firebase account. Enter this command to do so. 

    firebase init

    We need to select the “Hosting: Configure files for Firebase Hosting and …” We will need to use our arrow keys on our keyboard to interact with the CLI. Once you have moved down your arrow onto the row you want, press “SPACEBAR” on your keyboard to select and “ENTER/RETURN” to continue.

    Next, move your arrow keys to the row “Create a new project” as we are going to create a new project. Press “ENTER/RETURN” to confirm your selection.

    You are now required to provide a unique project id. This project is used for your project website domain. Give your project id the name* in this naming convention: “Stackupusername-stackup-threejs-intro”. Replace stackupusername with your Stackup Profile Name. In the event that the project id you wish to give is unavailable, do add numbers to your StackUp name to make the id unique. For example, instead of <stackie>- stackup-threejs-intro, you can give an id of <stackie823>-threejs-intro.

    *On naming your project id: It must be 6 to 30 lowercase letters, digits or hyphens. It must start with a letter. If your StackUp profile name does not meet this requirement, you should ensure that the stackupusername used in your project id is similar to your StackUp profile name. Otherwise, you will receive an error.

    Next, you will be asked for the project directory to look for. This directory is where Firebase will upload all the files to the cloud. When we built our application, Vite automatically created a dist folder for us. In your terminal, type in dist and right after, hit the “ENTER/RETURN” to confirm the folder.

    Important: Now Firebase is asking if you want them to rewrite all files into a single-page app. Hit “N” on your keyboard. If we press “Y”, it will overwrite all the code that we have in the index.html file.

    You may choose to upload your code here to GitHub as well. We will not need to do so, as such, select “N”.

    When Firebase asks to overwrite the index.html file that resides within the “dist” folder, hit “N” as we want to retain the current index.html file that we have written.

    Once you see the statement 'Firebase initialization complete!', we have completed setting up our project on Firebase. We may now move on to deploying our code.

    We are nearing the final step to deploy our code to the Internet. Open your terminal within your code editor and input the following command.

    firebase deploy

    We have now deployed the code to the internet. Firebase will also return the default link to access the project and you may use that “Hosting URL” to share with others.

    If you would like to make changes to your project after deployment, simply make your code changes and run the following commands in your terminal. The following commands will rebuild your web application and upload it to Firebase.

    npm run build
firebase deploy

    In the event you run into any errors with Firebase, you may visit Step 4 of this tutorial page for some frequently encountered errors and their solutions.

  • Step 12: Project Initialisation and Code Deployment (With Netlify)

    Firstly, we will need to install the Netlify CLI tool using the following command in your terminal:

    npm install netlify-cli -g

    You will also need to create an account on Netlify. Thereafter, ensure that you are logged in to Netlify on your browser.

    Next, we will obtain an access token so that you can deploy your project from your terminal. We will use the following command in your terminal:

    netlify login

    A new browser tab or window will be opened asking you to authorize Netlify CLI to access Netlify on your behalf. Click on the Authorize button. In the event that the browser tab or window is not opened, you can also copy the URL in your terminal and input it in your browser. Once authorization has been granted, your terminal should now have the message "You are now logged into your Netlify account!"

    Next, in your terminal, enter 

    netlify deploy

    You will come across the following prompts and these are the responses you should make:

    What would you like to do?: Create & configure a new site

    Team: <choose the default option>

    Site name: <yourusername>-threejs-intro (ensure you replace <yourusername> with your StackUp username)

    When asked to provide a publish directory, enter dist. Once the files have been uploaded, you will be provided with a "Website Draft URL". Go to that website and check that your website works as intended.

    If everything looks good, use the following command:

    netlify deploy --prod

    Once again, you will be asked for the publish directory. Use dist.

    When you see the message "Deploy is live!" and your website URL is provided, you know that your site has been successfully deployed. Visit your website again and ensure that everything works well.

  • Step 13: Stacking It Up!

    You have reached the end! 

    Web Link

    In this tutorial, you created a website and hosted it on Firebase, Netlify or Vercel. Your website should show a rotating cube.
